4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, a licensed veterinarian may
6 not render veterinary medical services, including
7 prescribing drugs, without establishing a
8 veterinarian-client-patient relationship.
9 This bill would prohibit a licensed veterinarian
10 from refusing to provide a written prescription upon
11 request, subject to certain conditions.
12 This bill would require a licensed veterinarain
13 to disclose that a client may request a written
14 prescription before dispensing a prescription
15 medication.
16 This bill would also require all veterinary
17 facilities to post a conspicuous sign notifying the
18 public of the fact that a client may request a written
19 prescription from his or her veterinarian.
20
21
22 A BILL
23 TO BE ENTITLED
24 AN ACT
25
26 Relating to veterinary medicine; to add Section
27 34-29-77.1 to the Code of Alabama 1975, to prohibit licensed
28 veterinarians from refusing to provide written prescriptions
Page 1

veterinarians from refusing to provide written prescriptions
HB616 INTRODUCED
29 upon request, subject to conditions; to require licensed
30 veterinarians to disclose certain information prior to
31 dispensing medications; and to require veterinary facilities
32 to post signage stating that clients may request written
33 prescriptions from his or her veterinarian.
34 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
35 Section 1. (a) For purposes of this section, the term
36 "written prescription" includes paper prescriptions via manual
37 transmission and electronic prescriptions via direct
38 transmission to a pharmacy.
39 (b) A licensed veterinarian may not refuse to provide a
40 written prescription to a client upon the client's request to
41 do so if:
42 (1) In the licensed veterinarian's medical opinion, the
43 prescription medication is medically safe for in-home
44 administration by the owner; and
45 (2) A valid veterinarian-client-patient relationship
46 exists.
47 (c) Before dispensing a prescription medication, a
48 licensed veterinarian, or an authorized member of the
49 veterinary staff, shall clearly inform a client that:
50 (1) The client may request to receive a written
51 prescription for the medication that may be filled at a
52 pharmacy of the client's choice; and
53 (2) If the veterinary facility is able to fill the
54 prescription, the client may have the prescription filled at
55 the facility.
56 (d) All veterinary facilities shall post a clear and
Page 2

(d) All veterinary facilities shall post a clear and
HB616 INTRODUCED
57 conspicuous sign near the primary public entrance or at the
58 primary point of sale or checkout that substantially states
59 the following:
60 "UNDER ALABAMA LAW, A VETERINARY CLIENT MAY RECEIVE A
61 WRITTEN PRESCRIPTION FROM HIS OR HER VETERINARIAN UPON REQUEST
62 THAT MAY BE FILLED BY A PHARMACY OF HIS OR HER CHOOSING."
63 (e) This section does not apply if:
64 (1) In the determination of a licensed veterinarian,
65 immediate dispensing of medication is necessary to preserve
66 the life or prevent the suffering of a patient; or
67 (2) The prescription is for a medication for which
68 dispensing is restricted by federal or state law.
69 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
70 1, 2026.
